Velocity increases margin for error and makes offspeed even more effective. I’m not sure if you notice in MLB games, but stuff guys aren’t pinpoint by any means.  Stuff>command

960214109928263681.text: @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics To further elaborate, if you can attack the zone with stuff, you’re going to keep your pitch counts down and get hitters into defensive counts where they are vulnerable to different pitches.  Pinpoint command is almost impossible to have.

960221602758692870.text: @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics There are a lot of factors that can go into that though. I’ve seen guys who had great command and good stuff that still get crushed. The fact is that if you have great stuff/velocity, you will get more opportunities to figure it out.

960221911258198016.text: @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics Good command guys may get 1 shot to prove themselves. If they fail, they get released. Then it’s really difficult to get back in because teams take guys with much better stuff. That’s just the way it is.

960223917897076737.text: @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics I disagree, the big leagues are a prime example that isn’t true. There are far more stuff guys now, even as starters, than pitchability. Attacking the zone with stuff is more important than trying to be perfect with average to fringe stuff.

960228293030096898.text: @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics Maddux early on was 91-94 with plus movement and command. People seem to forget those things. Also, it’s also impossible to answer that because the way training is now, they may be different pitchers. You’re talking exceptions though. It’s extremely difficult to be an exception.

960228836276428801.text: @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics They definitely wouldn’t be 300 game winners in today’s game. They’d be successful, but like I said, who knows how much better or worse they’d be with modern training programs.

960231951323074569.text: @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics As a HS/college prospect, 91-93 with good offspeed will get you a shot for sure.  It depends on what role an org would see you filling to determine where your velocity/stuff should be. 91-93 with movement and command would be considered at least above average grade.

960232633291722752.text: @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics Not sure about that.  Over a long season that would be difficult for pitchers to hold up depending upon the amount of games they throw in weekly.  Also factor in high leverage/stress pitches.  It’s tough to eliminate innings eaters altogether.

960235742726369280.text: @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics Absolutely man. My thought process has changed over time because of being open minded and willingness to learn. I never felt like I had it all figured out, because it was pretty much the opposite. I knew nothing, and still have a lot to learn.

960338946029948928.text: @lokationnation @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics If you look at my other posts, I think command and pitchability are important.  I just think being perfect with command unrealistic.  I’d prefer to teach guys to attack the zone with their best stuff.  Puts you in advantage counts more often than being trying to hit exact spots.

960339474961043457.text: @lokationnation @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics Being in advantage counts allows you to have more margin for error with not only pitch execution, but pitch selection.

960341853966094336.text: @lokationnation @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics I respect your opinion and your accomplishments. I think my train of thought is just a little different. I think if you get too wound up in making perfect pitches, it takes away from your aggressiveness in the zone. I would say a huge chunk of big leaguers aren’t at a 70% clip.

960342129582198790.text: @lokationnation @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics Their stuff and ability to get hitters into defensive counts allows them to have a higher margin for error. At the end of the day we want the same end result. Just slightly different processes of getting there.

960344877019131904.text: @lokationnation @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics I would say that the best have both plus stuff and execution. I think there more “good” pitchers who can rely on stuff and throwing strikes than guys who ride or die on execution. It also depends on what role you have, and other factors (deception, movement, spin rate, etc.)

960345371397578753.text: @lokationnation @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics There are so many different variables that go into this topic. I just would never want to take away the “attack” mentality away from someone because they’re hyper focused on execution and making “plus misses”.

960346240084008960.text: @lokationnation @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics From my experience, when I focused on just letting it rip, my sequencing improved, and I was able to attack the zone and execute. When I got wound up in making perfect pitches, I wouldn’t repeat the same patterns. I prefer the attack with your best mentality for that reason.

960347346646257669.text: @lokationnation @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics Which I agree with, but in a lot of instances, high velocity requires good sequencing and patterns. Repeating good patterns is easier than repeating difficult ones with energy leaks.

960348532854218753.text: @lokationnation @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics But it’s more difficult to repeat bad patterns than good ones if I’m not mistaken.

960349131649806337.text: @lokationnation @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics This has been a good conversation. I’ve just had experience in a command first program, and my command didn’t get better until I got over being perfect and attacking the zone with my best stuff. Maybe I’m just wired differently.

960349893758828544.text: @lokationnation @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics You could learn it yes, but if it messed up timing/energy in another area, then it’s harder to repeat in a game scenario. High level patterns have to be simpler because it allows more energy transfer throughout the delivery.

960351224888520705.text: @lokationnation @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics It can be trained indirectly while training other components though.  Whether it be a mentality, a pattern, building intent/velocity, having the feel of the baseball and your release is the core component of command. At least for me personally it does.

960351775873224704.text: @lokationnation @GatorCoachHodes @TreadAthletics I 100 percent agree with not having a cookie cutter approach.
